        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Latin Hip-Hop & ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        },
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Rap en Español ",
          "italic": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Dancehall's uptake in Panama and Puerto Rico was related to its counter-cultural connotations and close relationship with rap or hip-hop and thus sounds and images of modernity, urbanity, and Blackness. While roots reggae preached pan-African liberation, dancehall embraced more local concerns resonant with hip-hop: crime, drugs, violence, sex, poverty, and corruption. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The proto-reggaetón of the early 1990s drew almost equally on reggae and hip-hop. The artists of this period—"
        },
        {
          "text": "raperos",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " or "
        },
        {
          "text": "rapeadores",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " not yet "
        },
        {
          "text": "reggaetoneros",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "—expressed more of an artistic alignment to hip-hop than reggae, in particular the gangster rap of the 1980s, as a major stylistic influence. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "However, the \"Latin Rap\" or rap in Spanish performed by Puerto Ricans in New York was also a major influence. This subgenre did not diverge stylistically so much as linguistically from hip-hop's sonic template. Puerto Rico's Vico C stands as a foundational figure here, as the artist who first demonstrated that one could rap entirely and compellingly in Spanish (aside from the occasional insertion of hip-hop slang lyrics) and therefore the founder of "
        },
        {
          "text": "rap en español",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\"I sing hip-hop on top of a reggaetón beat. I don't know how to write it any other way\" (Tego Calderón, Marshall 2009 p. 27) "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Vico C describes reggaetón as \"essentially hip-hop, but with a flavor more compatible to the Caribbean\" (Chosen Few Documentary) "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Many interviewees in the Chosen Few documentary, for example, distinguish reggaeton from hip hop by noting that the former is more of a baile-centric genre, more appropriate for couple dancing that breaking, where focus is more on the beat than the lyrics. This comes directly from the genre's dancehall baseline and therefore overlap with a great number of Caribbean (dance) genres. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Afro-Panamanian ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        },
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Reggae en Español ",
          "italic": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
